{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Author is right -- English throughout block quote for experiment to work",
    "content": "The author is right. This changes my thinking about the *analysis* section, not just the block quote.\n\nI already supported English in the block quote. But the author's argument applies further: even in the author's own analysis, the reader needs to *feel* the terms to experience the reversal. If the author's analysis says \"we observe phenomenal Li, infer phenomenal Ren, generalize to De, abstract to Dao\" -- this is an opaque report. If it says \"we observe phenomenal ritual conduct, infer phenomenal humaneness, generalize to virtue, abstract to the Way\" -- the reader can follow the reversal because each term activates English associations that then get inverted.\n\nThis means: use full English translations throughout the *entire* passage -- block quote AND the author's analysis. The glossed first occurrence \"(humaneness (仁, ren))\" gives the reader the Chinese for cross-reference. But the running text must be English so the experiment works.\n\nThe one exception remains 德: \"virtue\" in the block quote shifts to \"(constitutive) character\" in the analysis, because that shift IS the experiment -- the reader feels \"virtue\" get deconstructed into \"character.\" This only works if \"virtue\" had semantic weight to begin with, which confirms the author's point exactly."
  }
}
